  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT116-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">iyaṟkaippuṇarcci puṇarntu nīṅkun talaimakaṉ taṉṉeñciṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">HE who leaves [her] after having consummated the natural union, speaking to [his] own heart.</p>
          </div>


        <div xml:id="KT116">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                yāṉayan tuṟaivō ṭēmpāy kūntal</l>
<l>                vaḷaṅkeḻu cōḻa ruṟantaip peruntuṟai</l>
<l>                nuṇmaṇa laṟalvārn taṉṉa</l>
<l>                naṉṉeṟi yavvē naṟuntaṇ ṇiyavē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l>
            <choice>
          <seg>The honey-scented<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tēmpāy</term> can also mean "frequented by bees": <term xml:lang="ta">pāy</term>, the verb of movement, might be explained as a means to activate the (metonymic?) association of tēm with bee.</note> tresses of her who is still<note place="foot">nayantu uṟaivōḷ: the most natural interpretation might here be one of uṟai-tal as an auxiliary verb with the aspect of continuity: she is one who is continuously longed for by him. See also KT 145.4 tuñcātu uṟainar, KT 65.4 vārātu uṟaiyunar.</note> the one I longed for,</seg>
          <seg>
            <lg>
              <l>The tresses swarmed by honey[-bees]<note place="foot">So TVG with Cām.; of course there is the topos of bees coming to women's hair.</note> of her whom I have</l>  
              <l>longed for [and with whom] I stay.</l>
            </lg>
        </seg>
           </choice>
        </l>
        <l rend="indent">like water<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṟal</term> can also be, with Cām., "black sand", that is, "like black sand flown over fine [white] sand"; thus unequivocally in KT 286.3, but equally certain is "water" in KT 65.1 – and in the KT there are just these 3 occurrences.</note> trickling over fine sand<note place="foot">Again the elliptical crossing of expressive levels: the white sand through which the water flows in curl-like, winding tracks evokes her face, otherwise not mentioned, and/or her white body which is contrasted by her black hair.</note></l>
        <l rend="indent">at the big ghat of Uṟantai, the [town of the] wealthy Cōḻar,</l>
        <l>[is] good [and]<note place="foot">Instead of taking nal "good" as a further predicate noun difficult to explain, the possibility of an adverb might be considered, i.e. "very curly".</note> curly. It [is] fragrant [and] cool.</l>

            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
